{"title_page": "Silvia Moreno-Garcia", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n|image = \n| name        = Silvia Moreno-Garcia\n| caption     = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1981|4|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Baja California]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation  = author\n| genre       = [[Speculative fiction]]\n| nationality = [[Mexico]]\n| period      = \n| movement    = \n| notableworks = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n}}\n'''Silvia Moreno-Garcia''' (born 25 April 1981) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] novelist, short story writer, editor, and publisher.\n\n==Early life==\nMoreno-Garcia was born April 25, 1981,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isni.org/0000+0001+1826+5005|title=ISNI 0000000118265005 Garcia, Silvia Moreno- ( born 1981-04-25 )|website=www.isni.org|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> and raised in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Silvia Moreno- Garcia|url=http://speculatingcanada.ca/2013/01/16/interview-with-silvia-moreno-garcia/|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Both her parents worked for radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Silvia Moreno-Garcia, author of Signal to Noise|url=http://www.mybookishways.com/2015/02/interview-silvia-moreno-garcia-author-of-signal-to-noise.html|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> She moved to Canada in 2004, where she presently lives with her family in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"ISFDB\">{{isfdb name|id=123813|name=Silvia Moreno-Garcia}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoreno-Garcia began her career publishing in various fiction magazines and books including [[Exile Editions|Exile Quarterly]]. She was a finalist for the 2011 [[Manchester Fiction Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mills|first1=Adam|title=Interview with Silvia Moreno-Garcia and Orrin Grey|url=http://weirdfictionreview.com/2013/03/interview-with-silvia-moreno-garcia-and-orrin-grey/}}</ref> Her first short story collection ''[[This Strange Way of Dying]]'' was published in September 2013 by [[Exile Editions]]. Her second collection, ''Love and Other Potions'' came out in 2014 from Innsmouth Free Press.<ref>http://www.silviamoreno-garcia.com/blog/bibliography/love-other-poisons/</ref> Her debut novel ''[[Signal to Noise (Moreno-Garcia novel)|Signal to Noise]]'' was published in 2015 by [[Solaris Books]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SIGNAL TO NOISE|url=http://www.solarisbooks.com/post/25|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe serves as publisher of Innsmouth Free Press, an imprint devoted to weird fiction.<ref>[http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/staff/ Innsmouth Free Press] - Staff</ref> With [[Paula R. Stiles]], she co-edited the books ''[[Cthulhu Mythos anthology#Historical Lovecraft|Historical Lovecraft]]'' (2011),\n''[[Future Lovecraft]]'' (2012), ''[[Sword and Mythos]]'' (2014), and ''[[Cthulhu Mythos anthology#She Walks in Shadows|She Walks In Shadows]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/books/historicallovecraft/|title=Innsmouth Free Press - ''Historical Lovecraft''|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/books/futurelovecraft/|title=Innsmouth Free Press - ''Future Lovecraft''|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/books/swordmythos/|title=Innsmouth Free Press - ''Sword and Mythos''|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/available-now/she-walks-in-shadows/|title=She Walks in Shadows|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020|via=www.innsmouthfreepress.com}}</ref> With [[Orrin Grey]], she co-edited ''Fungi'' (2013), a collection of \"fungal fiction\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/available-now/fungi/|title=Fungi|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020|via=www.innsmouthfreepress.com}}</ref> With [[Lavie Tidhar]], she edits ''The Jewish Mexican Literary Review''.<ref>[http://www.thejmlr.com/about-2/ ''The Jewish Mexican Literary Review''] - Editors</ref> In 2016, she won a World Fantasy Award for the anthology ''She Walks in Shadows'' and a Copper Cylinder Award for her novel ''Signal to Noise''.\n\nAs of October 2019 Moreno-Garcia is a book columnist for ''[[The Washington Post]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/the-weird-the-wacky-the-underappreciated-a-new-look-at-science-fiction-and-fantasy/2019/10/07/e74f9746-d953-11e9-ac63-3016711543fe_story.html|title=Review &#124; The weird, the wacky, the underappreciated: A new look at science fiction and fantasy|first1=Silvia|last1=Moreno-Garcia|first2=Lavie|last2=Tidhar|website=Washington Post|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 she was announced as a finalist for the Nebula Award 2019 in the Best Novel category for her book ''[[Gods of Jade and Shadow]]'' <ref name=\"Loc20\">{{cite web |url=https://nebulas.sfwa.org/2019-nebula-award-finalists-announced/ |title=2019 Nebula Award Finalists Announced |work=Science Fiction Writers Association |publisher=[[Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America|SFWA]] |accessdate=2020-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''[[This Strange Way of Dying]]'' (collection 2013)\n*''[[Love and Other Poisons]]'' (collection 2014)\n*''[[Signal to Noise (Moreno-Garcia novel)|Signal to Noise]]'' (novel 2015)\n*''[[Certain Dark Things]]'' (novel 2016)\n*''The Beautiful Ones'' (novel 2017)\n*''Prime Meridian'' (novella 2017)\n*''[[Gods of Jade and Shadow]]'' (novel 2019)\n*''Untamed Shore'' (novel 2020)\n*''Mexican Gothic'' (novel 2020) \n\n===As editor or co-editor===\n*''[[Cthulhu Mythos anthology#Historical Lovecraft|Historical Lovecraft]]'' (2011)\n*''Future Lovecraft'' (2012)\n*''Dead North'' (2013)\n*''Fungi'' (2013)\n*''Sword and Mythos'' (2014)\n*''[[Cthulhu Mythos anthology#She Walks in Shadows|She Walks In Shadows]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Nebula Awards Showcase 2019]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moreno-Garcia, Silvia}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Mexican emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Writers from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Women science fiction and fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Women horror writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n|image = \n| name        = Silvia Moreno-Garcia\n| caption     = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1981|4|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Baja California]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation  = author\n| genre       = [[Speculative fiction]]\n| nationality = [[Mexico]]\n| period      = \n| movement    = \n| notableworks = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n}}\n'''Silvia Moreno-Garcia''' (born 25 April 1981) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] novelist, short story writer, editor, and publisher.\n\n==Early life==\nMoreno-Garcia was born April 25, 1981,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isni.org/0000+0001+1826+5005|title=ISNI 0000000118265005 Garcia, Silvia Moreno- ( born 1981-04-25 )|website=www.isni.org|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> and raised in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Silvia Moreno- Garcia|url=http://speculatingcanada.ca/2013/01/16/interview-with-silvia-moreno-garcia/|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Both her parents worked for radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Silvia Moreno-Garcia, author of Signal to Noise|url=http://www.mybookishways.com/2015/02/interview-silvia-moreno-garcia-author-of-signal-to-noise.html|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> She moved to Canada in 2004, where she presently lives with her family in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"ISFDB\">{{isfdb name|id=123813|name=Silvia Moreno-Garcia}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoreno-Garcia began her career publishing in various fiction magazines and books including [[Exile Editions|Exile Quarterly]]. She was a finalist for the 2011 [[Manchester Fiction Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mills|first1=Adam|title=Interview with Silvia Moreno-Garcia and Orrin Grey|url=http://weirdfictionreview.com/2013/03/interview-with-silvia-moreno-garcia-and-orrin-grey/}}</ref> Her first short story collection ''[[This Strange Way of Dying]]'' was published in September 2013 by [[Exile Editions]]. Her second collection, ''Love and Other Potions'' came out in 2014 from Innsmouth Free Press.<ref>http://www.silviamoreno-garcia.com/blog/bibliography/love-other-poisons/</ref> Her debut novel ''[[Signal to Noise (Moreno-Garcia novel)|Signal to Noise]]'' was published in 2015 by [[Solaris Books]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SIGNAL TO NOISE|url=http://www.solarisbooks.com/post/25|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe serves as publisher of Innsmouth Free Press, an imprint devoted to weird fiction.<ref>[http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/staff/ Innsmouth Free Press] - Staff</ref> With [[Paula R. Stiles]], she co-edited the books ''[[Cthulhu Mythos anthology#Historical Lovecraft|Historical Lovecraft]]'' (2011),\n''[[Future Lovecraft]]'' (2012), ''[[Sword and Mythos]]'' (2014), and ''[[Cthulhu Mythos anthology#She Walks in Shadows|She Walks In Shadows]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/books/historicallovecraft/|title=Innsmouth Free Press - ''Historical Lovecraft''|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/books/futurelovecraft/|title=Innsmouth Free Press - ''Future Lovecraft''|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/books/swordmythos/|title=Innsmouth Free Press - ''Sword and Mythos''|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/available-now/she-walks-in-shadows/|title=She Walks in Shadows|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020|via=www.innsmouthfreepress.com}}</ref> With [[Orrin Grey]], she co-edited ''Fungi'' (2013), a collection of \"fungal fiction\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.innsmouthfreepress.com/blog/available-now/fungi/|title=Fungi|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020|via=www.innsmouthfreepress.com}}</ref> With [[Lavie Tidhar]], she edits ''The Jewish Mexican Literary Review''.<ref>[http://www.thejmlr.com/about-2/ ''The Jewish Mexican Literary Review''] - Editors</ref> In 2016, she won a World Fantasy Award for the anthology ''She Walks in Shadows'' and a Copper Cylinder Award for her novel ''Signal to Noise''.\n\nAs of October 2019 Moreno-Garcia is a book columnist for ''[[The Washington Post]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/the-weird-the-wacky-the-underappreciated-a-new-look-at-science-fiction-and-fantasy/2019/10/07/e74f9746-d953-11e9-ac63-3016711543fe_story.html|title=Review &#124; The weird, the wacky, the underappreciated: A new look at science fiction and fantasy|first1=Silvia|last1=Moreno-Garcia|first2=Lavie|last2=Tidhar|website=Washington Post|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 she was announced as a finalist for the Nebula Award 2019 in the Best Novel category for her book ''[[Gods of Jade And Shadow]]'' <ref name=\"Loc20\">{{cite web |url=https://nebulas.sfwa.org/2019-nebula-award-finalists-announced/ |title=2019 Nebula Award Finalists Announced |work=Science Fiction Writers Association |publisher=[[Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America|SFWA]] |accessdate=2020-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n==Bibliography==\n*''[[This Strange Way of Dying]]'' (collection 2013)\n*''[[Love and Other Poisons]]'' (collection 2014)\n*''[[Signal to Noise (Moreno-Garcia novel)|Signal to Noise]]'' (novel 2015)\